
# PHASE 8 — PRODUCTION KUBERNETES DEPLOYMENT

[## [SECTION: PART 1 — HELM CHART]]

#[## [SECTION: Step 1 — Chart Structure (Component #75)]]


1
03:07:06,000 --> 03:07:12,000
Now let's move to Phase 8. Production Kubernetes deployment.
We'll deploy the entire stack on AWS EKS using Helm.

2
03:07:12,000 --> 03:07:18,000
The Helm chart packages all Kubernetes manifests into a single versioned, configurable unit.
The key design principle is never hardcode anything.

3
03:07:18,000 --> 03:07:24,000
Every value that differs between environments lives in values.yaml.
And is overridden per environment.

4
03:07:24,000 --> 03:07:30,000
First, create infrastructure/helm/Chart.yaml.
This defines the chart metadata.

5
03:07:30,000 --> 03:07:36,000
apiVersion is v2. name is financial-rag-agent.
type is application. version is 0.1.0. appVersion is 1.0.0.

6
03:07:36,000 --> 03:07:42,000
We add keywords like rag, fintech, llm, pgvector, and fastapi.
And maintainers with name Cloudfrugal and email.

7
03:07:42,000 --> 03:07:48,000
Our chart structure is ready.
Now let's create the helpers template.


#[## [SECTION: Step 2 — Helpers Template (Component #76)]]


8
03:07:48,000 --> 03:08:00,000
Now let's create the helpers template.
We'll put it in infrastructure/helm/templates/_helpers.tpl

9
03:08:00,000 --> 03:08:06,000
First, define the name helper.
It expands the name of the chart using the nameOverride value.

10
03:08:06,000 --> 03:08:12,000
It truncates to 63 characters and trims any trailing dash.
This enforces Kubernetes' label value limit.

11
03:08:12,000 --> 03:08:18,000
Next, the fullname helper.
If fullnameOverride is provided, use it.
Otherwise, use the chart name.

12
03:08:18,000 --> 03:08:24,000
The chart helper returns the chart name and version.
With plus signs replaced by underscores.

13
03:08:24,000 --> 03:08:30,000
Now the labels helper.
This defines common labels applied to every resource.

14
03:08:30,000 --> 03:08:36,000
It includes helm.sh/chart, app.kubernetes.io/managed-by, and app.kubernetes.io/version.

15
03:08:36,000 --> 03:08:42,000
The selectorLabels helper is critical.
This is used in matchLabels and must be stable, never change.

16
03:08:42,000 --> 03:08:48,000
It includes only app.kubernetes.io/name and app.kubernetes.io/instance.
No chart version here. If chart version changes, the selector would mismatch.

17
03:08:48,000 --> 03:08:54,000
This is a common Helm mistake.
matchLabels is immutable after creation. If you include the chart version, every upgrade fails.

18
03:08:54,000 --> 03:09:00,000
The image helper constructs the full image reference.
It takes a global registry, an image repository, and a tag.

19
03:09:00,000 --> 03:09:06,000
If registry is provided, it returns registry slash repository colon tag.
If not, it returns repository colon tag.

20
03:09:06,000 --> 03:09:12,000
This allows the registry to be set globally while repository and tag vary per component.

21
03:09:12,000 --> 03:09:18,000
The podAnnotations helper merges global podAnnotations with per-component overrides.
It uses Helm's merge function for deep merging.

22
03:09:18,000 --> 03:09:24,000
Our helpers template is complete.
Now let's create the base values.


#[## [SECTION: Step 3 — Base Values (Component #75)]]


23
03:09:24,000 --> 03:09:30,000
Now let's create the base values.yaml file.
This defines the configuration for all environments.

24
03:09:30,000 --> 03:09:36,000
First, the global section.
image registry is empty, pullPolicy is IfNotPresent.

25
03:09:36,000 --> 03:09:42,000
podAnnotations, podLabels, nodeSelector, tolerations, and affinity are empty by default.
These will be overridden per environment.

26
03:09:42,000 --> 03:09:48,000
The namespace is set to financial-rag.

27
03:09:48,000 --> 03:09:54,000
Now the API section.
enabled is true. image repository is financial-rag-agent/api. tag is latest.

28
03:09:54,000 --> 03:10:00,000
replicaCount is 2. resources requests are 500 millicpu and 512 megabytes.
limits are 1000 millicpu and 1 gigabyte.

29
03:10:00,000 --> 03:10:06,000
service type is ClusterIP, port is 8000.
ingress is disabled by default.

30
03:10:06,000 --> 03:10:12,000
env sets LOG_LEVEL to info and WORKERS to 2.
envFrom references a secret called financial-rag-secrets.

31
03:10:12,000 --> 03:10:18,000
livenessProbe and readinessProbe both check /health on port 8000.
liveness has initialDelaySeconds 15, readiness has 10.

32
03:10:18,000 --> 03:10:24,000
HPA is enabled with minReplicas 2, maxReplicas 6.
targetCPUUtilizationPercentage is 70, targetMemoryUtilizationPercentage is 80.

33
03:10:24,000 --> 03:10:30,000
Now the agentPool section.
enabled is true. image repository is financial-rag-agent/agent. tag is latest.

34
03:10:30,000 --> 03:10:36,000
replicaCount is 2. resources requests are 500 millicpu and 1 gigabyte.
limits are 2000 millicpu and 2 gigabytes.

35
03:10:36,000 --> 03:10:42,000
env sets AGENT_CONCURRENCY to 4 and LOG_LEVEL to info.
livenessProbe checks /health on port 8001.

36
03:10:42,000 --> 03:10:48,000
HPA is enabled with minReplicas 2, maxReplicas 8.
targetCPUUtilizationPercentage is 65, targetMemoryUtilizationPercentage is 75.

37
03:10:48,000 --> 03:10:54,000
Now the ingestion CronJob.
enabled is true. image repository is financial-rag-agent/ingestion. tag is latest.

38
03:10:54,000 --> 03:11:00,000
schedule is 0 2 asterisk asterisk asterisk, which is 2 AM UTC daily.
concurrencyPolicy is Forbid to prevent overlapping runs.

39
03:11:00,000 --> 03:11:06,000
successfulJobsHistoryLimit and failedJobsHistoryLimit are both 3.
restartPolicy is OnFailure.

40
03:11:06,000 --> 03:11:12,000
resources requests are 250 millicpu and 512 megabytes.
limits are 1000 millicpu and 1 gigabyte.

41
03:11:12,000 --> 03:11:18,000
env sets INGESTION_BATCH_SIZE to 50 and LOG_LEVEL to info.

42
03:11:18,000 --> 03:11:24,000
Now the pgvector StatefulSet.
enabled is true. image repository is pgvector/pgvector. tag is pg16.

43
03:11:24,000 --> 03:11:30,000
replicaCount is 1. resources requests are 500 millicpu and 1 gigabyte.
limits are 2000 millicpu and 4 gigabytes.

44
03:11:30,000 --> 03:11:36,000
storage uses storageClassName gp3 and size 50 gigabytes.
service port is 5432.

45
03:11:36,000 --> 03:11:42,000
env sets POSTGRES_DB to financial_rag and POSTGRES_USER to raguser.
envFrom references the financial-rag-secrets secret.

46
03:11:42,000 --> 03:11:48,000
persistence is enabled.
livenessProbe and readinessProbe use pg_isready.

47
03:11:48,000 --> 03:11:54,000
Now the Redis StatefulSet.
enabled is true. image repository is redis. tag is 7-alpine.

48
03:11:54,000 --> 03:12:00,000
replicaCount is 1. resources requests are 100 millicpu and 256 megabytes.
limits are 500 millicpu and 512 megabytes.

49
03:12:00,000 --> 03:12:06,000
storage uses storageClassName gp3 and size 10 gigabytes.
service port is 6379.

50
03:12:06,000 --> 03:12:12,000
args enable appendonly, set maxmemory to 400 megabytes, and maxmemory-policy to allkeys-lru.
livenessProbe and readinessProbe use redis-cli ping.

51
03:12:12,000 --> 03:12:18,000
Finally, the serviceMonitor.
enabled is false by default. namespace is monitoring.
interval is 30 seconds. path is slash metrics.

52
03:12:18,000 --> 03:12:24,000
Our base values are complete.
Every workload follows a consistent pattern.


#[## [SECTION: Step 4 — Production Values Override (Component #99)]]


53
03:12:24,000 --> 03:12:30,000
Now let's create the production values override file.
We'll put it in infrastructure/helm/values.prod.yaml

54
03:12:30,000 --> 03:12:36,000
These override only the keys that differ from base values.
Helm merges the two files when deploying.

55
03:12:36,000 --> 03:12:42,000
First, global section.
image registry is set to your ECR registry URL. pullPolicy becomes Always.

56
03:12:42,000 --> 03:12:48,000
nodeSelector sets role to application.
tolerations for dedicated application nodes.

57
03:12:48,000 --> 03:12:54,000
podAnnotations enable prometheus.io/scrape and set the port to 8000.

58
03:12:54,000 --> 03:13:00,000
Now the API production overrides.
replicaCount is 5. image tag is pinned to 1.0.0, never latest in production.

59
03:13:00,000 --> 03:13:06,000
resources requests are 1000 millicpu and 1 gigabyte.
limits are 2000 millicpu and 2 gigabytes.

60
03:13:06,000 --> 03:13:12,000
env sets LOG_LEVEL to warning and WORKERS to 4.

61
03:13:12,000 --> 03:13:18,000
ingress is enabled. className is alb.
annotations configure the AWS ALB for internet-facing traffic.

62
03:13:18,000 --> 03:13:24,000
target-type is ip. listen-ports is HTTPS 443.
ssl-redirect is enabled. certificate-arn must be set.

63
03:13:24,000 --> 03:13:30,000
healthcheck-path is slash health.
group.name is financial-rag-prod.

64
03:13:30,000 --> 03:13:36,000
host is api.financial-rag.cloudfrugal.com.
tls secretName is financial-rag-tls.

65
03:13:36,000 --> 03:13:42,000
HPA minReplicas is 5, maxReplicas is 20.
targetCPUUtilizationPercentage is 60, targetMemoryUtilizationPercentage is 70.

66
03:13:42,000 --> 03:13:48,000
Now the agentPool production overrides.
replicaCount is 5. image tag is 1.0.0.

67
03:13:48,000 --> 03:13:54,000
resources requests are 2000 millicpu and 4 gigabytes.
limits are 4000 millicpu and 8 gigabytes.

68
03:13:54,000 --> 03:14:00,000
env sets AGENT_CONCURRENCY to 8 and LOG_LEVEL to warning.

69
03:14:00,000 --> 03:14:06,000
HPA minReplicas is 5, maxReplicas is 25.
targetCPUUtilizationPercentage is 55, targetMemoryUtilizationPercentage is 65.

70
03:14:06,000 --> 03:14:12,000
Now the ingestion production overrides.
image tag is 1.0.0. schedule is 0 1 asterisk asterisk asterisk, which is 1 AM UTC.

71
03:14:12,000 --> 03:14:18,000
resources requests are 1000 millicpu and 2 gigabytes.
limits are 2000 millicpu and 4 gigabytes.

72
03:14:18,000 --> 03:14:24,000
env sets INGESTION_BATCH_SIZE to 200 and LOG_LEVEL to warning.

73
03:14:24,000 --> 03:14:30,000
Now the pgvector production overrides.
resources requests are 2000 millicpu and 8 gigabytes.
limits are 4000 millicpu and 16 gigabytes.

74
03:14:30,000 --> 03:14:36,000
storage size is 500 gigabytes, storageClassName is gp3-iops.

75
03:14:36,000 --> 03:14:42,000
Now the Redis production overrides.
resources requests are 500 millicpu and 2 gigabytes.
limits are 1000 millicpu and 4 gigabytes.

76
03:14:42,000 --> 03:14:48,000
storage size is 50 gigabytes.
maxmemory is 3500 megabytes.

77
03:14:48,000 --> 03:14:54,000
Finally, the serviceMonitor is enabled.
namespace is monitoring. interval is 15 seconds.

78
03:14:54,000 --> 03:15:00,000
Key production differences.
Never use latest tag in production. If a pod restarts and pulls a new latest image, your production environment silently changes.

79
03:15:00,000 --> 03:15:06,000
Always pin to a specific semver tag or git SHA in production.
Our production values override is complete.


#[## [SECTION: Step 5 — StatefulSets: pgvector and Redis (Components #78–80)]]


80
03:15:06,000 --> 03:15:12,000
Now let's understand StatefulSets for pgvector and Redis.
Why StatefulSet, not Deployment?

81
03:15:12,000 --> 03:15:18,000
Deployments are for stateless workloads. Pods are interchangeable.
If a pod is replaced, local storage is lost.

82
03:15:18,000 --> 03:15:24,000
That's fine for the API. State lives in PostgreSQL.
But catastrophic for PostgreSQL itself.

83
03:15:24,000 --> 03:15:30,000
StatefulSets provide stable pod names.
fra-pgvector-0, not fra-pgvector-abc123.

84
03:15:30,000 --> 03:15:36,000
They provide stable DNS for pod-to-pod communication.
And ordered startup and shutdown.

85
03:15:36,000 --> 03:15:42,000
Most importantly, volumeClaimTemplates create a dedicated PVC per pod.
Each replica has its own persistent storage.

86
03:15:42,000 --> 03:15:48,000
The pgvector StatefulSet defines the image, ports, and environment variables.
It mounts pgdata from a volumeClaimTemplate.

87
03:15:48,000 --> 03:15:54,000
If persistence is enabled, it creates a PVC named pgdata.
With storageClassName and size from values.

88
03:15:54,000 --> 03:16:00,000
Two services for pgvector.
A headless service with clusterIP None for stable DNS.

89
03:16:00,000 --> 03:16:06,000
And a regular ClusterIP service that load-balances.
The API uses the regular service for read-write operations.

90
03:16:06,000 --> 03:16:12,000
The Redis StatefulSet follows the same pattern.
Stable pod names, persistent storage, headless service.

91
03:16:12,000 --> 03:16:18,000
Redis args enable appendonly persistence and set maxmemory-policy to allkeys-lru.
This is the correct eviction policy for a cache.

92
03:16:18,000 --> 03:16:24,000
Our StatefulSets are complete.
pgvector and Redis now have persistent storage.


#[## [SECTION: Step 6 — API and Agent Deployments (Components #81, #84)]]


93
03:16:24,000 --> 03:16:30,000
Now let's create the API and Agent Deployments.

94
03:16:30,000 --> 03:16:36,000
First, the security context applied to every workload.
runAsNonRoot true prevents running as user ID zero.

95
03:16:36,000 --> 03:16:42,000
allowPrivilegeEscalation false prevents setuid binaries from gaining root.
readOnlyRootFilesystem true prevents writing to the container filesystem.

96
03:16:42,000 --> 03:16:48,000
capabilities drop ALL removes all Linux kernel capabilities.
This is defense in depth.

97
03:16:48,000 --> 03:16:54,000
readOnlyRootFilesystem requires a tmp volume mounted at slash tmp.
We add an emptyDir volume for temporary files.

98
03:16:54,000 --> 03:17:00,000
The rolling update strategy controls how pods are replaced.
maxUnavailable one means at most one pod is down during upgrade.

99
03:17:00,000 --> 03:17:06,000
maxSurge two means at most two extra pods can run during upgrade.
With five replicas in production, you have fast rollouts without interruption.

100
03:17:06,000 --> 03:17:12,000
The API Deployment includes livenessProbe and readinessProbe on port 8000.
ServiceAccountName is set to the API service account.

101
03:17:12,000 --> 03:17:18,000
The Agent Deployment has an in-memory model cache.
emptyDir with medium Memory, size limit 500 megabytes.

102
03:17:18,000 --> 03:17:24,000
This is a tmpfs filesystem stored in RAM.
The local embedding model stays in memory between requests.

103
03:17:24,000 --> 03:17:30,000
Both Deployments have a ClusterIP service for internal communication.
The API service is used by the ALB Ingress.

104
03:17:30,000 --> 03:17:36,000
The Agent service is only for health checks, not external traffic.
Our Deployments are complete.


#[## [SECTION: Step 7 — HPAs (Components #83, #85)]]


105
03:17:36,000 --> 03:17:42,000
Now let's configure HorizontalPodAutoscalers.
The API HPA scales on CPU and memory utilization.

106
03:17:42,000 --> 03:17:48,000
Target CPU utilization is 70 percent, memory is 80 percent.
Minimum replicas 2, maximum 20 in production.

107
03:17:48,000 --> 03:17:54,000
The Agent HPA has lower thresholds, 55 percent CPU and 65 percent memory.
Agent loops are CPU-spiky during embedding and LLM inference.

108
03:17:54,000 --> 03:18:00,000
Both HPAs have asymmetric scale-up and scale-down behavior.
Scale up fast, scale down slow.

109
03:18:00,000 --> 03:18:06,000
The API scales up 4 pods per minute after a 60 second stabilization window.
It scales down 2 pods per 2 minutes after a 5 minute window.

110
03:18:06,000 --> 03:18:12,000
The Agent scales up 5 pods per minute after just 30 seconds.
But it scales down only 1 pod per 3 minutes after a 10 minute window.

111
03:18:12,000 --> 03:18:18,000
Why the difference? Agent reasoning loops can run for 30 to 60 seconds.
Removing a pod mid-loop drops the request.

112
03:18:18,000 --> 03:18:24,000
Our HPAs are complete.
The API and Agent will scale automatically based on load.


#[## [SECTION: Step 8 — Ingestion CronJob (Component #86)]]


113
03:18:24,000 --> 03:18:30,000
Now let's create the Ingestion CronJob.

114
03:18:30,000 --> 03:18:36,000
schedule is set from values, default 2 AM UTC.
concurrencyPolicy Forbid is critical.

115
03:18:36,000 --> 03:18:42,000
Without it, if one job runs longer than expected, the next starts concurrently.
Two concurrent ingestion jobs would exceed EDGAR's rate limit.

116
03:18:42,000 --> 03:18:48,000
And could corrupt the deduplication logic.
activeDeadlineSeconds is a 3 hour hard cap.

117
03:18:48,000 --> 03:18:54,000
If the job runs longer than that, Kubernetes kills it.
backoffLimit 2 means it retries at most twice on failure.

118
03:18:54,000 --> 03:19:00,000
The job uses a service account with IRSA annotations.
Same security context as other workloads.

119
03:19:00,000 --> 03:19:06,000
readOnlyRootFilesystem true with a tmp emptyDir.
Our ingestion CronJob is complete.


#[## [SECTION: Step 9 — ALB Ingress (Component #87)]]


120
03:19:06,000 --> 03:19:12,000
Now let's create the ALB Ingress.

121
03:19:12,000 --> 03:19:18,000
This creates an AWS Application Load Balancer for external traffic.
target-type ip routes traffic directly to pod IPs.

122
03:19:18,000 --> 03:19:24,000
Avoids the double-hop through kube-proxy.
ip mode requires pods to be in subnets the ALB can reach.

123
03:19:24,000 --> 03:19:30,000
Use private subnets with the ALB in public subnets.
group.name allows multiple Ingress objects to share one ALB.

124
03:19:30,000 --> 03:19:36,000
Without grouping, each Ingress creates a new ALB.
That would cost about $0.008 per hour, per ALB.

125
03:19:36,000 --> 03:19:42,000
Grouping saves money and management overhead.
The Ingress routes all traffic to the API service.

126
03:19:42,000 --> 03:19:48,000
TLS is terminated at the ALB using an ACM certificate.
Our ALB Ingress is complete.


#[## [SECTION: Step 10 — ServiceMonitor (Component #88)]]


127
03:19:48,000 --> 03:19:54,000
Now let's create the Prometheus ServiceMonitor.

128
03:19:54,000 --> 03:20:00,000
This tells Prometheus to scrape metrics from the API.
The label release equals kube-prometheus-stack is not arbitrary.

129
03:20:00,000 --> 03:20:06,000
The Prometheus operator only picks up ServiceMonitors that match its label selector.
If you installed kube-prometheus-stack with a different release name, change this label.

130
03:20:06,000 --> 03:20:12,000
namespaceSelector matches the financial-rag namespace.
selector matches pods with component api.

131
03:20:12,000 --> 03:20:18,000
endpoints specify port http, path slash metrics, interval 30 seconds.
honorLabels true preserves existing metric labels.

132
03:20:18,000 --> 03:20:24,000
Our ServiceMonitor is complete.
Prometheus will now scrape API metrics.


[## [SECTION: PART 2 — KARPENTER NODE PROVISIONING]]

#[## [SECTION: Step 11 — Karpenter IAM Role (Component #89)]]


133
03:20:24,000 --> 03:20:30,000
Now let's configure Karpenter for node provisioning.
Karpenter is AWS's modern node autoscaler for Kubernetes.

134
03:20:30,000 --> 03:20:36,000
Unlike the Cluster Autoscaler, Karpenter launches nodes directly.
It is much faster and more efficient.

135
03:20:36,000 --> 03:20:42,000
First, create the Karpenter IAM role.
We use eksctl to create the service account.

136
03:20:42,000 --> 03:20:48,000
The role needs permissions to run and terminate EC2 instances.
Describe instances and instance types.

137
03:20:48,000 --> 03:20:54,000
iam PassRole to pass the node IAM role to new instances.
And SSM GetParameter for AMI discovery.


#[## [SECTION: Step 12 — Karpenter Installation (Component #90)]]


138
03:20:54,000 --> 03:21:00,000
Now install Karpenter using the Helm chart.
Version 0.37.0 is stable.

139
03:21:00,000 --> 03:21:06,000
The service account annotation sets the IAM role.
Cluster name and interruption queue are required settings.

140
03:21:06,000 --> 03:21:12,000
Karpenter will now manage node scaling.
It launches nodes when pods are pending and consolidates when nodes are underutilized.


#[## [SECTION: Step 13 — EC2NodeClass and NodePools (Components #91–93)]]


141
03:21:12,000 --> 03:21:18,000
Now create the EC2NodeClass.
This defines what kind of EC2 instances Karpenter can launch.

142
03:21:18,000 --> 03:21:24,000
amiFamily is Amazon Linux 2.
The role is KarpenterNodeRole, which we create separately.

143
03:21:24,000 --> 03:21:30,000
Subnet selector terms look for tags.
karpenter.sh slash discovery equals the cluster name.

144
03:21:30,000 --> 03:21:36,000
Security group selector terms use the same tag.
Block device mapping uses gp3 with 50 gigabytes, encrypted.

145
03:21:36,000 --> 03:21:42,000
User data runs the EKS bootstrap script.
This joins the node to the cluster.

146
03:21:42,000 --> 03:21:48,000
Now create the first NodePool for the API.
This uses on-demand instances.

147
03:21:48,000 --> 03:21:54,000
On-demand nodes have consistent latency and no interruption risk.
Perfect for the API service.

148
03:21:54,000 --> 03:22:00,000
Instance families are m5, m6i, and m6a.
General purpose, consistent performance.

149
03:22:00,000 --> 03:22:06,000
Instance sizes are xlarge and 2xlarge.
A taint prevents pods that don't tolerate it from scheduling here.

150
03:22:06,000 --> 03:22:12,000
Disruption policy is WhenUnderutilized.
It consolidates after 5 minutes.

151
03:22:12,000 --> 03:22:18,000
Now create the second NodePool for ingestion.
This uses spot instances.

152
03:22:18,000 --> 03:22:24,000
Spot instances are up to 70 percent cheaper than on-demand.
But they can be interrupted at any time.

153
03:22:24,000 --> 03:22:30,000
Ingestion is idempotent. SHA-256 deduplication prevents duplicates.
If a spot instance is interrupted, the job just retries.

154
03:22:30,000 --> 03:22:36,000
Diverse instance families like m5, m6i, c5, and c6i.
Better spot availability across different types.

155
03:22:36,000 --> 03:22:42,000
Disruption policy is WhenEmpty, not WhenUnderutilized.
It consolidates after just 30 seconds.

156
03:22:42,000 --> 03:22:48,000
Why the difference? Spot nodes are ephemeral.
Don't keep expensive nodes idle longer than necessary.

157
03:22:48,000 --> 03:22:54,000
Apply all three resources with kubectl apply.
EC2NodeClass, api-ondemand NodePool, and ingestion-spot NodePool.

158
03:22:54,000 --> 03:23:00,000
Karpenter node provisioning is complete.
The cluster can now scale dynamically and cost-effectively.


[## [SECTION: PART 3 — TERRAGRUNT INFRASTRUCTURE]]

#[## [SECTION: Step 14 — Terragrunt Root Config (Component #94)]]


159
03:23:00,000 --> 03:23:06,000
Now let's set up Terragrunt for infrastructure provisioning.
Terragrunt wraps Terraform to provide DRY infrastructure code.

160
03:23:06,000 --> 03:23:12,000
One module definition, multiple environment instantiations.
Dev, staging, and prod each get their own configuration.

161
03:23:12,000 --> 03:23:18,000
First, create the root terragrunt.hcl file.
This is inherited by every environment module.

162
03:23:18,000 --> 03:23:24,000
The locals block reads the environment configuration.
It finds env.hcl in the parent folder.

163
03:23:24,000 --> 03:23:30,000
We extract the aws region, account ID, project name, and environment name.
The env name comes from the directory name.

164
03:23:30,000 --> 03:23:36,000
Next, remote state configuration.
State is stored in S3 with DynamoDB for locking.

165
03:23:36,000 --> 03:23:42,000
The bucket name combines project, account ID, and region.
The key includes environment and module path.

166
03:23:42,000 --> 03:23:48,000
DynamoDB table prevents concurrent state modifications.
This is critical for team workflows.

167
03:23:48,000 --> 03:23:54,000
Terragrunt generates the provider configuration at plan time.
It writes a provider.tf file into each module directory.

168
03:23:54,000 --> 03:24:00,000
We define required providers. AWS, Kubernetes, Helm, TLS, and Random.
All with specific version constraints.

169
03:24:00,000 --> 03:24:06,000
The AWS provider has default tags.
Project, environment, managed by, owner, and repo.

170
03:24:06,000 --> 03:24:12,000
This tags every AWS resource automatically.
No need to add tags manually to each resource.

171
03:24:12,000 --> 03:24:18,000
Finally, common inputs are passed to every module.
Project name, environment, AWS region, and account ID.

172
03:24:18,000 --> 03:24:24,000
Each module can access these without re-declaring them.
Our root Terragrunt config is complete.


#[## [SECTION: Step 15 — Environment Configs (Component #99)]]


173
03:24:24,000 --> 03:24:30,000
Now let's create the environment configurations.

174
03:24:30,000 --> 03:24:36,000
First, dev environment in env.hcl.
Development uses smaller, cheaper resources.

175
03:24:36,000 --> 03:24:42,000
VPC CIDR is 10.2.0.0 slash 16.
Two private subnets, two public subnets, two availability zones.

176
03:24:42,000 --> 03:24:48,000
EKS cluster version 1.29.
Node groups are t3 dot large for application, t3 dot medium for ingestion.

177
03:24:48,000 --> 03:24:54,000
Minimal sizes to keep costs low.
RDS uses db.t3.medium with 20 gigabytes of storage.

178
03:24:54,000 --> 03:25:00,000
Backup retention is just 1 day. Multi-AZ is false.
ElastiCache uses cache.t3.micro with one node.

179
03:25:00,000 --> 03:25:06,000
Now staging environment.
Staging should mirror production as closely as possible.

180
03:25:06,000 --> 03:25:12,000
VPC CIDR is 10.1.0.0 slash 16.
EKS version is still 1.29.

181
03:25:12,000 --> 03:25:18,000
Node groups use m5 dot xlarge for application, c5 dot large for ingestion.
Larger instances than dev.

182
03:25:18,000 --> 03:25:24,000
RDS uses db.r6g.large with 100 gigabytes of storage.
Backup retention is 7 days.

183
03:25:24,000 --> 03:25:30,000
ElastiCache uses cache.r6g.large.
Still single node to save cost.

184
03:25:30,000 --> 03:25:36,000
Finally, production environment.
This is where the actual costs run.

185
03:25:36,000 --> 03:25:42,000
VPC CIDR is 10.30.0.0 slash 16.
Three private subnets, three public subnets, three availability zones.

186
03:25:42,000 --> 03:25:48,000
EKS cluster version 1.30, the latest stable.
Node groups are for system workloads only.

187
03:25:48,000 --> 03:25:54,000
Note that Karpenter handles application and ingestion nodes.
The managed node group only runs system components.

188
03:25:54,000 --> 03:26:00,000
RDS uses db.r6g.xlarge with 500 gigabytes of storage.
Backup retention is 30 days. Multi-AZ is true for high availability.

189
03:26:00,000 --> 03:26:06,000
ElastiCache uses cache.r6g.large with two nodes.
Multi-AZ is true. Redis replicates across availability zones.

190
03:26:06,000 --> 03:26:12,000
Our environment configs are complete.
Each environment has its own isolated state and resources.


#[## [SECTION: Step 16 — Terragrunt Module Configs (Component #100)]]


191
03:26:12,000 --> 03:26:18,000
Now let's configure the Terragrunt child modules.
Each module handles one piece of infrastructure.

192
03:26:18,000 --> 03:26:24,000
Every module includes the root configuration and the environment configuration.
The terraform source points to the module directory.

193
03:26:24,000 --> 03:26:30,000
Inputs come from the environment locals.
Modules declare dependencies on other modules.

194
03:26:30,000 --> 03:26:36,000
The EKS module depends on the VPC module.
The RDS module depends on VPC and EKS.

195
03:26:36,000 --> 03:26:42,000
ElastiCache depends on VPC and EKS.
IAM depends on EKS and RDS for OIDC and secret ARNs.

196
03:26:42,000 --> 03:26:48,000
Terragrunt automatically orders applies based on these dependencies.
Notice the mock_outputs in each dependency block.

197
03:26:48,000 --> 03:26:54,000
These are used during terragrunt plan.
If the dependency hasn't been applied yet, mock outputs stand in.

198
03:26:54,000 --> 03:27:00,000
This allows planning the entire stack at once.
The ECR module is account-level, no VPC or EKS dependency.

199
03:27:00,000 --> 03:27:06,000
The S3 module is special. It creates the state bucket itself.
It has a chicken-and-egg problem.

200
03:27:06,000 --> 03:27:12,000
You need S3 for remote state, but you need Terraform to create S3.
The solution is to apply the S3 module first with a local backend.

201
03:27:12,000 --> 03:27:18,000
After the bucket exists, all other modules use it as remote state.
Our Terragrunt module configs are complete.


#[## [SECTION: Step 17 — Apply Order]]


202
03:27:18,000 --> 03:27:24,000
Now let's talk about apply order.

203
03:27:24,000 --> 03:27:30,000
Terragrunt automatically orders applies based on dependencies.
VPC first, then EKS, then RDS and ElastiCache in parallel, then IAM.

204
03:27:30,000 --> 03:27:36,000
To apply a full environment, go to the environment directory.
Run terragrunt run-all apply with non-interactive flag.

205
03:27:36,000 --> 03:27:42,000
To apply a single module, cd into its directory.
Then run terragrunt apply.

206
03:27:42,000 --> 03:27:48,000
The bootstrap sequence for a new environment is.
First, cd into the S3 module and apply it.

207
03:27:48,000 --> 03:27:54,000
Then you can apply all other modules.
The state backend is now configured.

208
03:27:54,000 --> 03:28:00,000
Our Terragrunt infrastructure is complete.
The entire AWS stack is now codified and repeatable.


#[## [SECTION: Step 18 — Deploy the Helm Chart]]


209
03:28:00,000 --> 03:28:06,000
Now that infrastructure is provisioned, let's deploy the Helm chart.
This installs the entire application on Kubernetes.

210
03:28:06,000 --> 03:28:12,000
First, create the namespace.
kubectl create namespace financial-rag.

211
03:28:12,000 --> 03:28:18,000
Then create the secrets. For production, these come from Vault.
For first deployment, you can create them manually.

212
03:28:18,000 --> 03:28:24,000
Always do a dry-run before deploying.
helm upgrade with dash dry-run and dash debug.

213
03:28:24,000 --> 03:28:30,000
This renders all templates and validates against the Kubernetes API.
It catches syntax errors before anything changes.

214
03:28:30,000 --> 03:28:36,000
Then deploy with dash wait and dash timeout 10 minutes.
Helm waits for all pods to become ready before completing.

215
03:28:36,000 --> 03:28:42,000
Verify with kubectl get pods.
You should see five pods running.

216
03:28:42,000 --> 03:28:48,000
API pods, agent pods, pgvector statefulset, and redis statefulset.
All with status Running.

217
03:28:48,000 --> 03:28:54,000
Our Helm deployment is complete.
The application is now running on Kubernetes.


#[## [SECTION: Common Errors and Fixes — Phase 8]]


218
03:28:54,000 --> 03:29:00,000
Let me walk through common errors in Phase 8.
And how to fix them.

219
03:29:00,000 --> 03:29:06,000
Error one. field is immutable on upgrade.
The cause is helm.sh/chart in matchLabels.

220
03:29:06,000 --> 03:29:12,000
The fix is to use selectorLabels in matchLabels.
And put helm.sh/chart only in metadata labels.

221
03:29:12,000 --> 03:29:18,000
Error two. ImagePullBackOff.
ECR is not authenticated.

222
03:29:18,000 --> 03:29:24,000
Run aws ecr get-login-password and pipe to docker login.
Or verify your IRSA role has ECR pull permissions.

223
03:29:24,000 --> 03:29:30,000
Error three. PVC stuck in Pending.
The gp3 storage class is not installed.

224
03:29:30,000 --> 03:29:36,000
Install the EBS CSI driver.
eksctl utils install-ebs-csi-driver.

225
03:29:36,000 --> 03:29:42,000
Error four. no nodes available.
Karpenter is not provisioning nodes.

226
03:29:42,000 --> 03:29:48,000
Check the Karpenter controller logs.
kubectl logs dash n karpenter deployment slash karpenter.

227
03:29:48,000 --> 03:29:54,000
Error five. HPA not scaling.
The metrics server is not installed.

228
03:29:54,000 --> 03:30:00,000
Apply the metrics server components from GitHub.
This provides the CPU and memory metrics that HPAs need.

229
03:30:00,000 --> 03:30:06,000
Error six. terragrunt S3 bucket not found.
The state bucket hasn't been created yet.

230
03:30:06,000 --> 03:30:12,000
Apply the S3 module first with local backend.
Then all other modules use it as remote state.

231
03:30:12,000 --> 03:30:18,000
Error seven. dependency cycle between modules.
Your dependencies form a circle.

232
03:30:18,000 --> 03:30:24,000
Check each dependency.config_path.
The graph must be a directed acyclic graph, or DAG.

233
03:30:24,000 --> 03:30:30,000
Error eight. ingestion pod not scheduled.
Missing spot capacity in your region.

234
03:30:30,000 --> 03:30:36,000
Add more instance families to the spot nodepool.
Diverse families have better spot availability.

235
03:30:36,000 --> 03:30:42,000
Error nine. connection refused to pgvector.
The pod is not yet ready.

236
03:30:42,000 --> 03:30:48,000
Check the readiness probe. pg_isready must pass before traffic is sent.
The pod may still be initializing.

237
03:30:48,000 --> 03:30:54,000
Bookmark this section.
When you hit an error, you'll know exactly where to look.


